field_data.Author: Scott
field_data.Sample Name: All RuO2 sputtered at 400C. Choongman 1 and 2 have had EC treatments
field_data.Removed from vacuum: All removed from sputter chamber Thursday. Choongman 1 cycled overnight from Thursday. Choongman 2 cycled yesterday.

notes: Started by leaving setup with a drop of water on for about 5 hours to replace the (18)OH groups in the vacuum chamber with (16)OH. When removing the drop (17500 s) there is an isotope effect in m/z=34 compared to 32. The effect is on the order of the exchange effect I am looking for on my samples. This is not okay. I decide to bake the chamber to remove the (18)O. Started heating at 19800 s. Turned heating power supply up to 90 V. Put a drop on. At 21200 s, turned heating power supply up to 120 V. m/z=20 has more pronounced respnse to heat than m/z=18, indicating that I am indeed stripping (18)O off the vacuum chamber. Interface block still cool to the touch. m/z=20 signal starts decreasing at 22000 s. At 22250 s, set heating voltage up to 150 V. m/z=20 increases again a bit but not as much as m/z=18. But they both increase faster and faster. Tons of CO2. Pressure in QMS increases to above 1e-6. I panic a bit, turn off heating, then back on, trying to catch 1e-6, but the outgassing seems to have been one-time. Now at 160, pressure keeps decreasing. Taking the petri dish cover off and putting it back on the interface block makes a huge difference in the signal (back on 23300 s). Going up to 170 V, it starts increasing again a bit. Fuck yes, now the m/z=34 to m/z=32 ratio goes straight to 0.4% when I remove the drop! (24800 s). 27700: Damnit, there's still a tiny deviation of m/z=32 and m/z=34 when I remove the drop. What the hell causes that? Also, the m/z=18 to m/z=20 ratio doesn't look so much better than it would have by exrapolation without the bake. Moral of the story: I MUST leave the setup with a drop overnight to stabilize the isotope background. New QMS file, timestamp 18:01:35 01... Choongman0. Looks good. 100 uA started at about 850 s, no deviation from the natural isotope ratio to see! Lots of bubble noise as expected given the huge chip on the sample. 02... Choongman1. Maybe there is something, but it's tiny, on the level of the noise. But I think it's there (link below). This sample seems somewhat less active than the previous. 03... Choongman2. Ahhh, damnit. I think, to a very good approximation, I've seen zero exchange. time to pack up and get the fuck out of here.
